snippet.textDisplay:
It is by far my favorite game of all time and thats with 30 years of gaming experience. I grew up with Zelda's Awakening as my first game and always held an insane amount of respect for music in games since then. 
Golden Sun, MGS and Tales of Symphonia ebbed the way just further that music is everything and since then I never respected games without good music anymore. 
IT HAS BECOME SO NEGLIGENT to put amazing music and voice acting in a game when it is PARAMOUNT to gameplay and storytelling to give it atmosphere and soul. 
Everyone in Kepler and Sandfall should be proud to have pathed a new gaming era for us to come where developers might think twice what to prioritize in their game. 
This has become a star in gaming history that no one will ever forget.

snippet.textDisplay:
I bought this game just out of pure coincidence. I was so saturated with typical triple A games and wanted to go more indie.
So I heard of this game, the title interested me and what I got, blew my off my socks.
It is my personal Game of the Year, but I would be disappointed, if that game didn't win at LEAST best OST.
Everytime I hear that soundtrack I get goosebumps and tears start rolling, it is just so beautiful.

Thank you to EVERYONE at Sandfall interactive for that absolute wonderful peace of a video game as well as a very very emotional soundtrack.

Love you all <3

snippet.textDisplay:
Lot tryed translate so gathered some clue : The song ‚ÄúAlicia‚Äù is written in a pseudo-Occitan or Occitan-inspired conlang ‚Äî a constructed poetic language designed to mimic the rhythm and emotion of Medieval Occitan (spoken in southern France during the 12th‚Äì14th centuries). It was intentionally created to carry emotional weight while hiding narrative meaning, which is only revealed later in the game .
This approach is common in storytelling-focused games ‚Äî for example:
Shadow of the Colossus used a fictional language blending Japanese and Latin tones
NieR Replicant featured songs in ‚ÄúChaos Language,‚Äù built for mood over meaning

In ‚ÄúAlicia,‚Äù the invented lyrics help preserve the mystery of the story while evoking southern French identity, memory, and loss. so you need bit of imagination can be something like this:
[Verse]
What did you leave behind?
I am forsaken.
The child is lost.
The fire, the veil, the canvas.
The child is gone.

[Chorus]
Maelle is calling.
The memory of us fades.
Alicia is calling.
Verso is breaking.
Lune is here.

[Verse]
What have you let go of?
I am forsaken.
The child is lost.
The fire, the veil, the canvas.
The child is gone.

[Chorus]
Maelle is calling.
The memory of us fades.
Alicia is calling.
Verso is breaking.
Lune is here.

snippet.textDisplay: Dude, I lost my father about 2 years ago, as a victim of suicide, and this game and the story behind it, made me feel very welcomed... I would like to talk more about it, but I will try not to give too many spoilers... but I was very happy playin the game, and at the end of the game, you have a certain path that you can choose, without wanting to spoil too much, but I wanted to stay longer in the game, I was able to understand all the feelings that the game wanted to convey and I didn't want it all to end, whoever finished it, understood what It meant... and I almost made a choice that theoretically would be wrong, because of a feeling that I also had... I prolonged the ending until the last moment and when the final decision of the game came and appeared, I spent about 10 minutes reflecting... and I was like "wow, I can understand both choices"... and after I made a certain choice and saw the prologue, I thought, "we have to accept things as they are, and not as we want them to be..." and I simply got a tattoo to make a mask of one of the characters in the game to do on my arm... this game really touched me... for me,this game is meant to be forever in my heart and in my skin, to remember that we cannot change the thins, when someone falls, we continue... I can completely understand Alicia's feelings, SPOILER...... just like Alicia, I understand the feeling of wanting to stay in that reality forever, and of feeling guilty for something that wasn't your fault

snippet.textDisplay:
What I like about is this song, is the expression of the singer.

The song is sad and give some sort of despair. But seeing Alice Duport-Percier sing it at the same time multiply those sentiments.

She isn't simply singing something beautiful. She's *living* the song, in a personal way, to a point that she looks "haunted" at the end, just by singing it,.

PS : I don't know if "haunted" is the right word to say here, if any english speaker know abtter one, please enlighten this frenchman here.

Yes...your success will also be the end...like with everything else things get worse if they get popular and the company behind it gets bigger with more shareholders and less detication and love behind it.

snippet.textDisplay:
Mrs. Duport-Percier ‚Äì I've been following your career for many years, ever since you worked with the Grissini Project. It makes my heart soar to see and hear you perform. You deserve all the praise in the world.
To Mr. Testard and the rest of the ensemble ‚Äì hats off, good people. You‚Äôve rocked my world and, I‚Äôm sure of it, the world of many others as well. üôå

I first heard this theme when the original trailer was released, and it made my heart skip a beat. I knew this game would be something special just from seeing and hearing the first 16 seconds of the video. Then, when the full version of "Alicia" was published, it instantly became a daily must-listen for me and my six-year-old daughter, Alicja. Once I started the game and reached the main menu, it took me a long time to decide I was ready to stop listening and begin the adventure.

I wish all games were made with such care and respect for the musical aspect of the medium.

I wish all games were made with such care and respect for the musical aspect of the medium.

snippet.textDisplay:
I wish the last act in Expedition33 wasn't about an addicted child's fight with her father, but was related to the world of the map. Because in the beginning you get a completely different plot connected with this beautiful and interesting world, and at the end the plot is about something else. You get a dissonance. I came to play one thing - and at the end of the other in terms of the story :(

I would dream of a ‚Äòclean ending‚Äô - where they ‚Äòclean up‚Äô everything unnecessary at the canvas, returning it to what it was - without the creations of his mother and father, without Maelle and the split, without the whole generation of people (including Gustave and the others). That is, to a state where only the interesting and bizarre creatures created by Verso live. And the canvas itself is sent under the lock of a safe with no way to get there. Isn't it a sorrowful and sad ending, which, nevertheless, is not reduced to a banal addiction to the virtual world, but teaches to appreciate and not to interfere in other people's creations, even if it can temporarily help with the grief of loss?

With this one, my love began the moment that song was released.
The weight of every word‚Ä¶ it was overwhelming. Beautiful. Painful.
But then you play the game‚Äîand you realize the pain isn‚Äôt just in the lyrics. It‚Äôs in the story. It‚Äôs in the atmosphere. It‚Äôs in the quiet, beautiful moments that ache just as much as the tragic ones.
This game deserves its crown. It‚Äôs GOTY material. It belongs in the hall of the greatest games of the past nine years.
And Lumiere‚Ä¶ Lumiere deserves to live on.

snippet.textDisplay:
It's really good to see The Grissini Project (Italian Breadsticks) and Orchestra Curieux (Curiosity Orchestra) receive some of their dues!

For those that are not aware, Ms. Duport-Percier, the vocalist here, as well as the instrumentalists have been covering video game and anime music for years now at a very professional level. Their covers include The Witcher, Final Fantasy XV, Nier Automata, Legend of Zelda, and Studio Ghibli. I believe they are French-speakers (Ils parlent Francais) from Switzerland (Suisse). Presumably, they all go to the same elite music school. In my personal opinion, they are among the best, if not the best, kept secret of unrecognized talent that YouTube has to offer. 

I fully agree with the fellow comment (from @Roze_aye) that this song NEEDS to be performed at the game awards!
-Jon from Canada.
